entry.title: Apply Latin-ASCII transliteration for address comparison.
entry.content:
We did not consider 'Str.' and 'Straße' as equivalent in German

addresses because our normalization rules contained a "strasse" ->

"str" rule and no "straße" -> "str" rule. The ß was not transliterated

for the comparison.



Similarly the street name "Iłłakowiczówny" and "Illakowiczowny" were

not considered equivalent because "ł" is not a composition of a letter

and a nonspacing mark (diacritic).



These problems are fixed with the CL.



It remains to introduce German transliteration for umlauts (ü -> ue)

for addresses from German speaking countries.

entry.title: Modify sequence local storage so that ComPtrs can be used with it.
entry.content:
With https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4957333,

a call to & on the template parameter T was added. This made it so that

if a ComPtr is stored in a SequenceLocalStorageSlot, it would get

released automatically upon the first read.



The root cause is that ComPtr has an operator override for &

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/cppcx/wrl/comptr-class?view=msvc-170#operator-ampersand

calling & releases the interface associated with the ComPtr.



Since ComPtr is common on windows and root causing bugs from this is

challenging, this change fixes SequenceLocalStorageSlot to avoid

calling & on the template and instead use std::addressof.

entry.title: TaskAttribution: Ensure CPED is cleared for upcoming per-Isolate CPED
entry.content:
[Get|Set]ContinuationPreservedEmbedderData is being refactored to store

CPED on the isolate rather than the context in v8. But without changing

blink to use the new API, we can have a situation where resetting the

CPED when a task scope is destroyed fails if the context is gone (e.g.

detached frame). Previously this wasn't a problem because the data was

stored on the context, but with per-isolate CPED, this can leak the

context / propagate wrong values.



This CL works around this by clearing the utility context's CPED. With

per-Context CPED, this essentially does nothing, but when the

per-Isolate CPED v8 changes land, this will clear the per-Isolate data.



Note: this is only temporary and will be removed once the v8 changes

land, in favor of using the new API.

entry.title: Make Frame IDs case-insensitive
entry.content:
Frame IDs are 128-bit hex strings. Today the only place we stringify

them is immediately after generating them in JS. However, in the near

future, we will also start passing them around as

base::UnguessableTokens (which internally are pairs of uint64), and

turning them back into hex strings when we need to ask the

WebFramesManager for a frame pointer.



Because Frame IDs will be hex-stringified by different languages and

libraries, with different casing conventions, we shouldn't assume the

case will always be consistent. By having the WebFramesManager always

lowercase the IDs it receives, we can be robust to this variance.

entry.title: Discard printer query after canceled system print dialog.
entry.content:
After clicking the system print dialog from the print preview popup,

if the cancel button is clicked, the cookie will be set to its invalid

cookie value in PrinterQuery::GetSettingsDone(). Then, in

PrintViewManagerBase::OnPrintSettingsDone(), the printer_query will be

added to the PrintQueriesQueue. Since the added cookie is the invalid

cookie value, the PrintViewManagerBase::ReleasePrinterQuery() cannot

retrieve the printer_query corresponding to the current_cookie.



This issue can to system print request causes the printer query with

the invalid cookie to be reused, and that has old state information

which can cause bad behavior. For out-of-process printing it causes a

crash, or otherwise it causes the system print dialog to not be modal.



These problems go away if the printer query with invalid cookie is not

saved when the dialog is canceled.



Bug: 1497945,1501053

entry.title: Make MIDI enterprise policies also block MIDI_SYSEX
entry.content:
crrev.com/c/4664576 introduced enterprise policies for controlling the

permissions related to Web MIDI.



These policies could set the MIDI permission to block, but would not

affect the MIDI_SYSEX permission. However, the MIDI_SYSEX permission

must never be in a more permissive state than the MIDI permission.



Fix this by modifying the permissions which can set MIDI to BLOCK to

also affect MIDI_SYSEX.



Note that since the DefaultMidiSetting does not have an ALLOW option,

we still cannot set MIDI_SYSEX to default ALLOW. This is by design,

since MIDI_SYSEX is considered significantly more dangerous than MIDI.

entry.title: UrlBar: do not compute scroll position if text layout is unavailable.
entry.content:
At the core, the change marks scroll position as "Pending" if Layout

is not available. This is done by enhancing the condition in

scrollDisplayText() with a getLayout() == null check.



The condition itself was the only condition in scrollDisplayText(),

otherwise the call was just a simple proxy to

scrollDisplayTextInternal(). The two methods have been collapsed by

relocating the check.



We permit calculation of the offset even if the current scroll type is

NO_SCROLL. This is because the method may still fall back to

SCROLL_TO_BEGINNING if the text is empty; evaluation of the scroll

position seems appropriate in that context and shouldn't depend on

whether current measure/layout pass has completed.



Lastly, the method pushes the resolution of the scoll directon until

*after* the layout() pass has completed (previously was: until after

onLayout() has completed), because this is the only time when the

layout is truly resolved and isLayoutRequested() will return false,

unblocking the pending scrollDisplayText fulfilment. The pushed method

deduplicates mPreviousScrolledViewWidth and mPreviousWidth which both

closely tracked the same underlying thing.



Note: the proper fix here calls for usage of getHintLayout(), however

this call is TextView private. Added lots of tests.

entry.title: Invalidate root scrollbars after color scheme flags changes
entry.content:
When the root or page color scheme changes from `light` to `normal`

and vice versa, the update after style change is not triggered for the

root scrollable area. This prevents the required invalidation of

scrollbars for the UsedColorSchemeRootScrollbars. The scrollbars

eventually can change the color upon interactions like hover/press

events, which leads to the inconsistent state and look. The scrollbar

corner will remain unchanged until the full invalidation is scheduled.



This happens because no computed style values are changed in this

case, and the GetDocument().GetLayoutView()->SetStyle() is not being

called, which prevents the call of the PLSA::UpdateAfterStyleChange().

The computed color scheme for the document remains `light` while the

PLSA::UsedColorSchemeScrollbars() returns `dark`.



The CL fixes the issue by adding `ColorSchemeFlagsIsNormal` bool

primitive to the computed style. Changes for the value will trigger

the style update and invalidate root scrollbars. The perf overhead

is expected to be limited due to the low number of root/page

color-scheme during the document lifecycle.



Also, the changes will prevent redundant scrollbars invalidations

which happened with the previous implementation. For example, after

any events which invoke document style changes which should not cause

scrollbars invalidations, e.g., unrelated JS style or page zooming

changes.



When the UsedColorSchemeRootScrollbars feature was enabled and

primary conditions were met (user's preferred color scheme is dark

and the computed CSS color-scheme value is normal), the

PLSA::UsedColorSchemeScrollbars() used to always return `dark` while

ComputedStyle::UsedColorScheme() returned `light`.



Now, for this case, we trigger invalidation only if related style

properties have changed and avoid problematic UsedColorScheme() vs

UsedColorSchemeScrollbars() comparison.

entry.title: Introduce SkipTPCDMitigationsWithAdsHeuristic feature
entry.content:
Introduces a disabled by default feature which allows skipping

TPCD mitigation checks when the cookie access is tagged as being used

for advertising purposes.



This means that cookies will continue to be blocked for cookie accesses

on ad requests even if the 3PC mitigations would otherwise allow the

access.



This is integrated via a new set of CookieSettingOverrides.



Each individual mitigation is given an override and an equivalent

feature param to allow more flexibility.

entry.title: [iOS] Remove duplicate RemoveObserver() in SafetyCheckObserverBridge.
entry.content:
SafetyCheckObserverBridge may incorrectly call

IOSChromeSafetyCheckManager's RemoveObserver() multiple times.



This can happens via first calling RemoveObserver() when

SafetyCheckObserverBridge's ManagerWillShutdown() is called.

Additionally, IOSChromeSafetyCheckManager's RemoveObserver() may be

called in SafetyCheckObserverBridge's destructor.



To address this, a new method `-managerWillShutdown` will be added to

`SafetyCheckManagerObserver`, notifying observers to reset their

`SafetyCheckManagerObserver` observations at the correct time.
